Etymology 1[edit]

From prō- +‎ cadō (“fall”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈproː.ki.doː/, [ˈproː.kɪ.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈpro.t͡ʃi.do/, [ˈprɔː.t͡ʃi.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

prōcidō (present infinitive prōcidere, perfect active prōcidī); third conjugation, no passive, no supine stem

  1. I fall forwards, down or flat; collapse.
  2. (of part of the body) I fall down or forwards out of place.

Etymology 2[edit]

From prō- +‎ caedō (“cut; strike”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /proːˈkiː.doː/, [proːˈkiː.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /proˈt͡ʃi.do/, [prɔˈt͡ʃiː.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

prōcīdō (present infinitive prōcīdere, supine prōcīsum); third conjugation, no perfect stem

  1. I strike down.
Conjugation[edit]
  • Third conjugation, but with no perfect conjugation.
